🏗️ Data Architecture
Automated Employee Onboarding & Offboarding System

Data Architecture defines how employee data is structured, stored, moved, secured, and synchronized across HR, IT, IAM, and workflow systems.

1. High-Level Architecture Overview

The system follows a layered + event-driven architecture:

[ UI Layer ]
     ↓
[ API Gateway ]
     ↓
[ Workflow Engine ]
     ↓
[ Service Layer ]
     ├── HR Service
     ├── IAM Service
     ├── Access Control Service
     ├── Document Service
     ├── Audit Service
     ↓
[ Data Layer ]
     ├── PostgreSQL (Core Data)
     ├── Object Storage (Documents)
     ├── Log Store (Audit Logs)
     ├── Event Bus (Kafka / Queue)
2. Core Data Domains
2.1 Employee Domain

Stores master employee information.

Employee
- employee_id (PK)
- name
- email
- department
- designation
- status (ACTIVE / EXITED / INACTIVE)
- joined_date
- exit_date
2.2 Access Control Domain

Manages roles and permissions.

UserRole
Role
Permission
RolePermission

Key relationships:

Employee → Role (many-to-many)
Role → Permissions (many-to-many)
2.3 Workflow Domain

Tracks onboarding/offboarding processes.

WorkflowInstance
- id
- employee_id
- type (ONBOARDING / OFFBOARDING)
- status
- created_at
- updated_at
2.4 Document Domain

Handles HR and compliance documents.

Document
- document_id
- employee_id
- type (NDA, Offer Letter, Exit Form)
- storage_url
- signed_status

Stored in:

Object Storage (S3-like system)
2.5 Audit Domain

Immutable logs for compliance.

AuditLog
- log_id
- employee_id
- action
- performed_by
- timestamp
- metadata
3. Logical Data Flow
3.1 Onboarding Flow
HR System
   ↓
Employee Data Created
   ↓
Workflow Engine Trigger (NEW_HIRE)
   ↓
IAM Service → Create Access
   ↓
Access Control Service → Assign Roles
   ↓
Document Service → Store Signed Docs
   ↓
Audit Service → Log All Actions
3.2 Offboarding Flow
Exit Request
   ↓
Approval Workflow
   ↓
IAM Service → Revoke Access
   ↓
Access Control → Remove Roles
   ↓
Document Archive
   ↓
Audit Log Finalization
   ↓
Employee Status = EXITED
4. Physical Data Architecture
4.1 Primary Database (Relational)
PostgreSQL / MySQL
Stores:
Employees
Roles
Permissions
Workflow states
4.2 Object Storage
Stores:
Contracts
NDAs
Exit documents

Example:

s3://company-hr-docs/employee_id/document.pdf
4.3 Event Streaming Layer

Used for real-time sync:

Kafka / RabbitMQ

Events:

EMPLOYEE_CREATED
ACCESS_GRANTED
EXIT_APPROVED
ACCESS_REVOKED
4.4 Audit Log Store
Append-only database or log system
Cannot be modified (immutability requirement)
5. Data Flow Architecture (Event-Driven)
[HR System]
    ↓ EMPLOYEE_CREATED
[Event Bus]
    ↓
[Workflow Engine]
    ↓
[IAM Service] → Access Granted
    ↓
[Audit Service] → Log Event
6. Data Consistency Model
6.1 Strong Consistency

Used for:

Employee status updates
Access revocation

Ensures immediate correctness.

6.2 Eventual Consistency

Used for:

Reports
Analytics dashboards
Sync across external systems
7. Data Storage Strategy
Data Type	Storage	Reason
Employee records	PostgreSQL	Structured relational data
Roles/Permissions	PostgreSQL	Strong consistency
Documents	Object Storage	Large binary files
Logs	Log DB / Elastic	Fast querying
Events	Kafka	Real-time processing
8. Data Security Architecture
8.1 Encryption
At rest → AES-256
In transit → TLS 1.2+
8.2 Access Control Layer
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
Least privilege principle
API-level authorization checks
8.3 Data Isolation
HR data separated from IT access data
Audit logs isolated (immutable store)
9. Data Lifecycle Architecture
CREATE → ACTIVE → UPDATE → EXIT → ARCHIVE → DELETE

Rules:

ACTIVE → EXIT only via approval workflow
ARCHIVE before deletion
DELETE only after retention period
10. Scalability Design
Horizontal scaling of API services
Partitioned employee tables (by department or region)
Event-driven async processing
Read replicas for reporting
11. Data Integrity Layer (Embedded Rules)
Foreign key enforcement
Transactional workflows (ACID)
Duplicate prevention logic
Schema validation at API layer
12. Disaster Recovery Architecture
Daily database backups
Multi-region storage replication
Point-in-time recovery (PITR)
Event replay using Kafka logs
